Lab 7 : Data Tidying, Transformation and Visualization with COVID-19 reporting data

Author

Madlyn

On the Computer

Loading the Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)

Loading data from a github repository

download.file(
  url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/master/csse_covid_19_data/csse_covid_19_time_series/time_series_covid19_confirmed_global.csv",
  destfile = "data/time_series_covid19_confirmed_global.csv",
  showWarnings = FALSE
)
time_series_confirmed <- read_csv("data/time_series_covid19_confirmed_global.csv")|>
  rename(Province_State = "Province/State", Country_Region = "Country/Region")

Data Tidying - Pivoting

time_series_confirmed_long <- time_series_confirmed |> 
               pivot_longer(-c(Province_State, Country_Region, Lat, Long),
                            names_to = "Date", values_to = "Confirmed")

Dates and times

time_series_confirmed_long$Date <- mdy(time_series_confirmed_long$Date)

Making Graphs from the time series data

time_series_confirmed_long|> 
  group_by(Country_Region, Date) |> 
  summarise(Confirmed = sum(Confirmed)) |> 
  filter (Country_Region == "US") |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date,  y = Confirmed)) + 
    geom_point() +
    geom_line() +
    ggtitle("US COVID-19 Confirmed Cases")

Several countries on the same graph

time_series_confirmed_long |> 
    group_by(Country_Region, Date) |> 
    summarise(Confirmed = sum(Confirmed)) |> 
    filter (Country_Region %in% c("China","France","Italy", 
                                "Korea, South", "US")) |> 
    ggplot(aes(x = Date,  y = Confirmed, color = Country_Region)) + 
      geom_point() +
      geom_line() +
      ggtitle("COVID-19 Confirmed Cases")

Graph with US data

time_series_confirmed_long_daily <- time_series_confirmed_long |>
  group_by(Country_Region, Date) |>
  summarise(Confirmed = sum(Confirmed), .groups = "drop") |> 
  arrange(Country_Region, Date) |>
  group_by(Country_Region) |>
  mutate(Daily = Confirmed - lag(Confirmed, default = 0)) |> 
  ungroup()
time_series_confirmed_long_daily |> 
    filter (Country_Region == "US") |> 
    ggplot(aes(x = Date,  y = Daily, color = Country_Region)) + 
      geom_point() +
      ggtitle("COVID-19 Confirmed Cases")

A line graph

time_series_confirmed_long_daily |> 
    filter (Country_Region == "US") |> 
    ggplot(aes(x = Date,  y = Daily, color = Country_Region)) + 
      geom_line() +
      ggtitle("COVID-19 Confirmed Cases")

Curved fit

time_series_confirmed_long_daily |> 
    filter (Country_Region == "US") |> 
    ggplot(aes(x = Date,  y = Daily, color = Country_Region)) + 
      geom_smooth() +
      ggtitle("COVID-19 Confirmed Cases")

Generalized Additive Model (GAM)

time_series_confirmed_long_daily |> 
    filter (Country_Region == "US") |> 
    ggplot(aes(x = Date,  y = Daily, color = Country_Region)) + 
      geom_smooth(method = "gam", se = FALSE) +
      ggtitle("COVID-19 Confirmed Cases")

Animated Graphs with gganimate

Installing gganimate and gifski

library(gganimate)
library(gifski)
theme_set(theme_bw())

An animation of the confirmed cases in select countries

daily_counts <- time_series_confirmed_long_daily |> 
      filter (Country_Region == "US")

p <- ggplot(daily_counts, aes(x = Date,  y = Daily, color = Country_Region)) + 
        geom_point() +
        ggtitle("Confirmed COVID-19 Cases") +
# gganimate lines  
        geom_point(aes(group = seq_along(Date))) +
        transition_reveal(Date) 

# make the animation
 animate(p, renderer = gifski_renderer(), end_pause = 15)
 anim_save("daily_counts_US.gif", p)

Animation of confirmed deaths

download.file(url="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/master/csse_covid_19_data/csse_covid_19_time_series/time_series_covid19_deaths_global.csv", 
  destfile = "data/time_series_covid19_deaths_global.csv")

Data tidying, pivot and time

time_series_deaths_confirmed <- read_csv("data/time_series_covid19_deaths_global.csv")|>
  rename(Province_State = "Province/State", Country_Region = "Country/Region")

time_series_deaths_long <- time_series_deaths_confirmed |> 
    pivot_longer(-c(Province_State, Country_Region, Lat, Long),
        names_to = "Date", values_to = "Deaths") 

time_series_deaths_long$Date <- mdy(time_series_deaths_long$Date)

Making the animated graph

p <- time_series_deaths_long |>
  filter (Country_Region %in% c("US","Canada", "Mexico","Brazil","Egypt","Ecuador","India", "Netherlands", "Germany", "China" )) |>
  ggplot(aes(x=Country_Region, y=Confirmed, color= Country_Region)) + 
    geom_point(aes(size=Confirmed)) + 
    transition_time(Date) + 
    labs(title = "Cumulative Deaths: {frame_time}") + 
    ylab("Deaths") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust=1))
# make the animation
animate(p, renderer = gifski_renderer(), end_pause = 15)

Three interrelated rules make a dataset tidy: 1. Each variable is a column; each column is a variable. 2. Each observation is a row; each row is an observation. 3. Each value is a cell; each cell is a single value.

Consistent data structures makes using tools easier. R vectors are optimized.

# Compute rate per 10,000
table1 |>

5.2.1 Exercises

  1. For each of the sample tables, describe what each observation and each column represents.

For table 1, the columns represent: 1. The name of the country 2. Year of the observation 3. Number of cases 4. Total population for the year For this table, each observation represents number of cases and total population for a country in a given year.

For table 2, the columns represent: 1. The name of the country 2. Year of observation 3. The type of variable represented in column 4 *This data isnât tidy 4. The actual value of the variable mentioned in column 3 For this table, each observation represents either the number of cases or total population for a country in a given year.

For table 3, the columns represent: 1. The name of the country 2. Year of the observation 3. The ratio of two observations dividing cases by population to determine a rate *This data isnât tidy For this table, each observation is a rate. It provides a ration of two observations, mainly cases and population

  1. Sketch out the process youâd use to calculate the rate for table2 and table3. You will need to perform four operations:
  1. Extract the number of TB cases per country per year. For table2, filter the rows where type == âcasesâ to obtain the number of cases for each country and year.
cases_tbl <- table2 |> filter(type == "cases") |> select(country, year, cases = count)

For table3, extract the numerator from the rate column (the value before the /) to get the number of cases.

table3_split <- table3 |> separate(rate, into = c("cases", "population"), sep = "/")
  1. Extract the matching population per country per year. For table2, filter the rows where type == âpopulationâ to obtain the corresponding population for each country and year.
pop_tbl <- table2 |> filter(type == "population") |> select(country, year, population = count)

For table3, extract the denominator from the rate column (the value after the /) to get the population.

table3_split <- table3_split |> mutate(
    cases = as.numeric(cases),
    population = as.numeric(population)
)
  1. Divide cases by population, and multiply by 10000. For table2, divide the number of cases by the corresponding population (making sure the country and year match for each pair) and multiply by 10,000.
rates <- left_join(cases_tbl, pop_tbl, by = c("country", "year")) |>
           mutate(rate = cases / population * 10000)

For table3, divide the numerator by the denominator and multiply by 10,000 â or directly evaluate the expression stored in the rate column.

table3_rates <- table3_split |> mutate(rate_per_10000 = cases / population * 10000)
  1. Store back in the appropriate place. For table2, add a new set of rows where type == ârateâ, with the calculated values stored in the count column.
rate_rows <- rates |> transmute(country, year, type = "rate", count = rate)
table2_with_rate <- bind_rows(table2, rate_rows)

For table3, convert the rate column from a text expression into a numeric value representing the rate per 10,000 people. However, this transformation will remove the original case and population details, since they are combined into one column.

table3_final <- table3_rates |> select(country, year, cases, population, rate_per_10000)

5.3.2 How does pivoting work?

Working with a simple data set:

df <- tribble(
  ~id,  ~bp1, ~bp2,
   "A",  100,  120,
   "B",  140,  115,
   "C",  120,  125
)

Adding variables to our dataset: ID, Measurement, and Value

df |> 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = bp1:bp2,
    names_to = "measurement",
    values_to = "value"

5.4.1 How does pivot_wider() work?

df <- tribble(
  ~id, ~measurement, ~value,
  "A",        "bp1",    100,
  "B",        "bp1",    140,
  "B",        "bp2",    115, 
  "A",        "bp2",    120,
  "A",        "bp3",    105
)

Take from value column and the names from the measurement column:

df |> 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = measurement,
    values_from = value
  )
# A tibble: 2 Ã 4
  id      bp1   bp2   bp3
  <chr> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
1 A       100   120   105
2 B       140   115    NA
#> # A tibble: 2 Ã 4
#>   id      bp1   bp2   bp3
#>   <chr> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
#> 1 A       100   120   105
#> 2 B       140   115    NA

Determine measurements:

df |> 
  distinct(measurement) |> 
  pull()
[1] "bp1" "bp2" "bp3"
#> [1] "bp1" "bp2" "bp3"
df |> 
  select(-measurement, -value) |> 
  distinct()
# A tibble: 2 Ã 1
  id   
  <chr>
1 A    
2 B    
#> # A tibble: 2 Ã 1
#>   id   
#>   <chr>
#> 1 A    
#> 2 B

pivot_wider() combines results:

df |> 
  select(-measurement, -value) |> 
  distinct() |> 
  mutate(x = NA, y = NA, z = NA)
# A tibble: 2 Ã 4
  id    x     y     z    
  <chr> <lgl> <lgl> <lgl>
1 A     NA    NA    NA   
2 B     NA    NA    NA   
#> # A tibble: 2 Ã 4
#>   id    x     y     z    
#>   <chr> <lgl> <lgl> <lgl>
#> 1 A     NA    NA    NA   
#> 2 B     NA    NA    NA

Fill in data:

df <- tribble(
  ~id, ~measurement, ~value,
  "A",        "bp1",    100,
  "A",        "bp1",    102,
  "A",        "bp2",    120,
  "B",        "bp1",    140, 
  "B",        "bp2",    115
)

Attempt to pivot:

df |>
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = measurement,
    values_from = value
  )
# A tibble: 2 Ã 3
  id    bp1       bp2      
  <chr> <list>    <list>   
1 A     <dbl [2]> <dbl [1]>
2 B     <dbl [1]> <dbl [1]>

#> list-cols.

Exercise 2:

Instead of making a graph of 5 countries on the same graph as in the above example, use facet_wrap with scales=âfree_yâ.

time_series_confirmed_long_daily |>
  filter(Country_Region %in% c("US", "Italy", "Brazil", "India", "France")) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = Daily, color = Country_Region)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "gam", se = FALSE, show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~Country_Region, scales = "free_y") +
  ggtitle("COVID-19 Confirmed Cases by Country (Daily)") +
  labs(x = "Date", y = "Confirmed Cases") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(strip.text = element_text(face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

Plot the cumulative deaths in the US, Canada and Mexico (you will need to download time_series_covid19_deaths_global.csv)

time_series_deaths_long |>

Exercise 5:

Make a graph with the countries of your choice using the daily deaths data

top5_countries <- time_series_deaths_long |>

Exercise 6:

Make an animation of your choosing (do not use a graph with geom_smooth)

vaccine_start <- as.Date("2021-04-19")

us_data <- time_series_deaths_long |>
  filter(Country_Region == "US") |>
  group_by(Date) |>
  summarise(Daily_Deaths = sum(Deaths, na.rm = TRUE)) |>
  mutate(Vaccination_Phase = ifelse(Date < vaccine_start, "Before Vaccine", "After Vaccine"))

p <- ggplot(us_data, aes(x = Date, y = Daily_Deaths, color = Vaccination_Phase)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  geom_point(aes(group = seq_along(Date))) +
  labs(
    title = "COVID-19 Deaths in the US Before and After Vaccine Availability",
    x = "Date",
    y = "Daily Deaths"
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(hjust = 1)) +
  transition_reveal(Date)

animate(p, renderer = gifski_renderer(), end_pause = 15)
anim_save("us_vaccine_effect.gif", p)
